public class IntroDPQOddEven extends IntroOddEven implements IntroDPQ<Comparable>
IntroDPQ (Dual Pivot Quick) Odd-even (Brick) Sort is a hybrid sorting algorithm that combines the strengths of Dual Pivot Quick Sort and Odd-even Sort. It aims to provide fast average-case performance while maintaining worst-case guarantees. The basic idea behind Intro Sort is to start with Dual Pivot Quick Sort, which is known for its efficiency on average, but has a worst-case time complexity of O(n^2) in certain scenarios. To mitigate the risk of Dual Pivot Quick Sort's worst-case behavior, Odd-even Sort monitors the recursion depth during the sorting process. If the depth exceeds a certain threshold, the algorithm switches to HeapSort, which guarantees worst-case O(n log(n)) time complexity but has higher overhead. Additionally, for small subarrays, Intro switches to Odd-even Sort, which has good performance for small input sizes.

    • IntroDPQOddEven

      public IntroDPQOddEven()
      IntroDPQ (Dual Pivot Quick) Odd-even (Brick) Sort:
      Is a hybrid sorting algorithm that combines the strengths of Dual Pivot Quick Sort and Odd-even Sort. It aims to provide fast average-case performance while maintaining worst-case guarantees. The basic idea behind Intro Sort is to start with Dual Pivot Quick Sort, which is known for its efficiency on average, but has a worst-case time complexity of O(n^2) in certain scenarios.

      To mitigate the risk of Dual Pivot Quick Sort's worst-case behavior, Odd-even Sort monitors the recursion depth during the sorting process. If the depth exceeds a certain threshold, the algorithm switches to HeapSort, which guarantees worst-case O(n log(n)) time complexity but has higher overhead. Additionally, for small subarrays, Intro switches to Odd-even Sort, which has good performance for small input sizes.

      Example:
      1. It checks if the size of the sub-array length is larger than INTRO_SIZE. If it is, it proceeds with the intro sort algorithm. If not, it uses insertion sort to sort the sub-array.
      2. If the maximum recursion depth is 0, it directly to sort the sub-array using a Intro Odd-even sorting algorithm. This is a base case to prevent excessive recursion.
      3. If the sub-array size is larger than INTRO_SIZE and the maximum recursion depth is not 0, it performs the following steps:
      4. Partition the sub-array and obtain the pivot indices.
      5. Recursively on the three sub-arrays:
      6. From left to elements smaller than the first pivot
      7. From elements between the two pivots
      8. From elements greater than the second pivot
      9. The recursion depth is decremented by 1 in each recursive call.
      10. If the sub-array size is smaller or equal to INTRO_SIZE, perform insertion sort on the sub-array.
      Note:
      Recursively applies the intro sort algorithm to sort a given array. It switches to insertion sort when the sub-array size becomes small enough. The maximum recursion depth is used to limit the depth of recursion to prevent excessive stack usage.

      Property:
      Worst Case Complexity: O(n^2)
      Best Case Complexity: O(n log(n))
      Average Case Complexity: O(n log(n))
      Auxiliary Space: O(log(n))
      Stability: No
